Dear YA,

Just to reiterate, if you do care about the estimates of variability
of effect sizes at different levels (i.e., variance components), then
you can use metafor in conjunction with the clubSandwich package to
enter a simple guesstimate of the correlation among effect sizes. You
can use a range of "r" values, not just .6.

Then, you can separately plot your estimates of fixed effects and
variance components to examine how sensitive your results are to the
choice of "r". In the end, you may find out that given a specific
range of "r", your results are stable. And you should clearly report
that.

However, if you think you can obtain the effect correlations perhaps
by contacting the primary studies' authors, you have my best wishes.

Cheers,
Reza


