Another way I found to calculate experiment-control pre-post test design SMD is

Morris, S. B. . (2008). Estimating effect sizes from pretest-posttest-control group designs.&nbsp;Organizational Research Methods,&nbsp;11(2), 364-386.


Morris calculated the SMD by&nbsp;


SMD = cp * (((mean_post_exp - mean_pre_exp) - (mean_post_ctrl - mean_pre_ctrl)) / sd_pre)


where&nbsp;


cp = 1- 3/(4(n_exp+n_ctrl - 2) -1)


and&nbsp;


sd_pre = sqrt(((n_exp - 1)*sd^2_pre_exp+(n_ctrl -1)*sd^2_pre_ctrl) / (n_exp +n_ctrl -2))


There are people talking about this approach online. Do you think it is still a common practice today?








