Dear Norman

This is not a direct answer to your question but it is an example of 
where small studies differ from large studies perhaps because of some 
moderator variable.

Colleagues carried out a multi-centre trial of a skills-based therapy 
intervention. Prior to that there had been a number of small 
single-centre studies which had in general been positive about the 
intervention. Our large study was by contrast neutral about its effect. 
It was felt that it was very unlikely that there were other studies the 
team did not know about so the small study effect was unlikely to be due 
to publication bias. It was felt more likely that the small studies had 
better control over the intervention because they involved a single 
therapist, usually someone keen on research, whereas the multi-centre 
study involved a range of therapists of different skill levels and 
different engagement with the research. It is always hard with 
skills-based therapies to assess fidelity with the intervention. I 
suspect a similar phenomenon can be found in other areas - small studies 
are just different on other dimensions apart from their size.

Michael


